Attraction at Intermediate Distances. One of the remarkable features of the effective interaction Δ, calculated self-consistently by accounting for the simultaneous screening of topological and electrostatic correlations, is that Δ(r) is attractive at intermediate distances comparable to the correlation length ξ in low salt concentration solutions. This attraction emerges despite the fact that all interacting segments bear the same sign for the charge. In the limit of low added salt concentration, Δ(r) is given by the double screening theory
