where z is an effective coordination number for neighboring interactions and εij are the van der Waals energies for contacts between segments i and j. In general, the temperature dependence of χ can be quite complex. However, in simple polymer solutions, χ is written as
χ= Θ
2T (76)
where Θ is the Flory temperature arising from all εij. The
tremendous success of the Flory−Huggins theory is that it predicts liquid−liquid phase separation for χ above a certain critical value χc. The phase diagram is composed by plotting χ
against the volume fraction of a component, say A, φ. The critical point is given by
